#ScamAlert:
Have you received a “traffic violation ticket” by email? 
DO NOT PAY IT—IT’S A SCAM.

This scam involves sending fake traffic tickets by email and asking for immediate payment through a link. Police do not issue tickets by email or even ask for your email during a traffic stop. 

Remember to never click on suspicious links or provide personal information to an untrusted source. 

Learn how to protect yourself from scams: http://ow.ly/SrRg306ATTq

caption_original: Here we are, four biologists (two in front, one way in the back, and yours truly behind the camera), installing a fence through a small tree-lined wetland at the Last Mountain Lake National Wildlife Area (NWA), Saskatchewan. We need fences like this one to keep our local “vegetation managers”() from wandering off the NWA and onto the roads and neighbouring properties. They munch away to keep our grasslands healthy! It took a lot of elbow grease to install this -km fence. We worked on it in our spare time, over about months, and we had to start bright and early to avoid the blistering summer heat. (Hipwaders are hot at the best of times.) But at least we had the mosquitos to keep us company! - Kerry

caption_original: Oh BUOY! What a boat! Come on board! The Canadian Coast Guard Ship (CCGS) Limnos calls Burlington, Ontario, its home, where it is docked at the Canada Centre for Inland Water (more often than knot). Puns are totally intended. Taking its name from “limnology,” the study of inland waters, CCGS Limnos is the dedicated scientific vessel for our environmental research and monitoring on the Great Lakes. It is capable of sampling the water, using a wide array of equipment, and it is equipped with an on-board laboratory for the processing and analysis of samples. How neat is that?

caption_original:
The magnificent Ferruginous Hawk, with a wingspan that can reach 1.5 m, is one of the largest species of hawks. Once found widely across the prairie provinces, its population has declined by almost two-thirds since 1992 due largely to habitat loss! Today, this majestic bird is listed as threatened under the Species at Risk Act.

To help give ferruginous hawks and other wildlife species a chance to thrive, Environment and Climate Change Canada is partnering with Nature Conservancy of Canada to conserve more than 1,200 hectares of prairie grassland in Alberta's Porcupine Hills region. This land will be protected in perpetuity under the Government of Canada’s Ecological Gifts Program. http://ow.ly/vk9F3060ACR

Canada is at the 3rd International Illegal Wildlife Trade Conference in Hanoi, Vietnam where delegates from around the world came to consensus on measures to reduce wildlife crime. Global leaders such as the Duke of Cambridge, Prince William, are attending along with Canada’s Ambassador to be part of the discussion in helping eradicate illegal wildlife trade and better protect wild species from the threat of extinction. 

Canada’s position in these discussions is to promote strong opposition to wildlife crime internationally through enhanced law enforcement strategies and promoting the sustainable use of wildlife in order to safeguard Canada’s legal international trade. caption_original:
Each year, thousands of shorebirds and waterfowl can be seen on the beaches and lagoons of Miscou Island, off the coast of New Brunswick, during their fall migration. The Government of Canada is pleased to partner with Nature Conservancy of Canada to protect an additional 47 hectares of this ecologically-sensitive wetlands habitat.

By protecting the lands from development, this area will continue to serve as an important refuge for migratory birds such as the Piping Plover, listed as endangered under the Species at Risk Act. 

Conserving coastal lands like these also benefits local communities by helping to mitigate the impacts of storms and rising sea levels associated with climate change. http://ow.ly/2cYz306wOnw

By protecting the lands from development, this area will continue to serve as an important refuge for migratory birds such as the Piping Plover, listed as endangered under the Species at Risk Act. Conserving coastal lands like these also benefits local communities by helping to mitigate the impacts of storms and rising sea levels associated with climate change.

Dr. Tyler Stephenson at the University of Calgary is using both to help his research related to oil viscosity. Over the past 150 years, our nation has made important investments in Canadian infrastructure, such as the national railway and the Trans-Canada Highway. We continue to make these transformative investments in our communities, in our country, and in our future. 

Work is currently underway in many communities across Canada to rebuild our infrastructure and find innovative ideas to tackle social, environmental and urban mobility challenges. 

As we look forward to celebrating Canada’s 150 anniversary, we want to highlight some of the projects that will be completed in communities across Canada in 2017. 

We look forward to hearing from you about infrastructure projects in your community. 

Be part of the conversation. Please use @INFC_eng or @INFC_fra on Twitter and #Canada150.
